Knowing a number of people into mine exploration, the concept of
"mineshafts where traffic isn't a problem" doesn't quite work. As soon
as a shaft is found where traffic isn't a problem (i.e. a newly
re-discovered mine), then traffic will become a problem with mine
explorers. And the occasional caver out for a bit of something
different.
From the point of view of sealing up commercially operating
mines at the end of operations, I don't quite see the point either.
Most of the threat of subsidence these days comes from lost mines, not
modern near-surface workings (a non-existent category?). Most tunnels
you can back-fill with spoil while you're running your mine down, and
you leave the last set of roof props in place made of wood, which will
rot and collapse over a few centuries, leading to a gradual diminution
of the problem.
So, what's the point of using fairly toxic chemicals in quite
large quantities to fill up holes in the ground which aren't much of a
problem? Gas build up (otherwise known as a CBM opportunity)?
Preventing public liability to snotty-nosed little scrotes (you
collapse the first mile or so of tunnel - you only have to make
"reasonable efforts" to protect the casual public).
--
Aidan Karley, FGS,
Aberdeen, Scotland
