We are looking at a number of shafts which have been backfilled with a
timber cap at rockhead level and mine tailings placed to fill the upper
part of the shaft within drift deposits up to 30m deep.  The shafts
themselves extend to depths of several hundred metres.  The problem is
principally relating to shafts not mineworkings or adits. Several have
collapsed recently and are therefore a hazard to locals and farm animals
at least, as well as to walkers (these are on the boundary of the Lake
District National Park).

There are also shafts closer to villages and towns as well as some
within these villages and towns which therefore endanger property and
the local community.  The majority of these mines closed down during the
depression of the 1920's so the degree to which they have been capped is
uncertain.

Completely open shafts are not the principal concern either.

As to the gas problem this is generally CO2 with some CH4 from the
backfill material where household refuse has been used.
