Ah. "Deads". So named for what the do to people who walk under them,
after the timber has been rotting for a few centuries.
Or even a few decades.
For a vertical shaft, I'd be dubious of the stability and strength
of things like builder's foam over even one century, let alone several.
You're going to have to do at least some inspection and engineering of the
shaft walls to be sure of getting a grip that would last a century. Which
means you're likely to have to haul out at least some of the fill ... nope,
I don't see that working. There's a word in caving for when you're under a
roof that is supported by 2/10 of bugger-all. We call it "hanging death" ;
the etymology should be obvious. If you've got shaft cappings that are made
of timber covered with rubble, I think that you're onto a non-starter in
trying to stabilise the rubble without removing it. Well, you might be able
to drive a (concrete) beam through the rubble pile from the side and let it
settle onto the bedrock on either side (with sufficient clearance to allow
for collapse of the lining of the shaft over centuries). But the excavation
costs of that sort of job would be up in the same range as digging out the
rubble and timber bracing, then replacing the lot with a proper concrete
cap and soil/ spoil back-fill.

